EduPair is a tutoring platform built to help tutors spend more time teaching, and less time managing messages, schedules, homework, and payments.

We accept tutors worldwide, and prior tutoring experience is not required.

Tutors on EduPair teach a wide range of areas, including:

A Levels, GCSEs, IB, SATs, HKDSE

University interviews and personal statements

Tech and finance internship applications

Academic writing and career guidance

EduPair uses AI to match students with suitable tutors, while also allowing students to browse tutor profiles directly.

As a tutor, you set your own subjects, exam boards, and rates, and manage everything from one dashboard. Payments are handled automatically via Stripe.

Tutors can teach online from anywhere, and those based in Hong Kong or the UK may also offer in-person lessons.

Signing up takes around five minutes, is completely free, and has no commitment.

EduPair is based in the UK and Hong Kong, and built for tutors globally.

In 2024, global spending on nuclear weapons highlights how major world powers continue to prioritize military strength and strategic deterrence. Countries like China, the United Kingdom, Russia, and France follow, reflecting their long-term focus on nuclear capabilities as part of national security and global influence.

Emerging and regional powers such as India, Israel, Pakistan, and North Korea spend comparatively less, yet their investments remain significant due to regional tensions and security concerns. While nuclear weapons are often justified as tools of deterrence, the rising expenditure also raises serious questions about global peace, arms races, and resource allocation. At a time when the world faces challenges like poverty, climate change, and healthcare crises, massive spending on nuclear arms sparks debate on priorities.

This data serves as a reminder of the fragile balance of power in international relations. It encourages discussions on arms control, disarmament, and the need for diplomatic solutions to conflicts. Understanding these numbers helps us see where the world stands todayâ€”and where it might be headed tomorrow.

I am currently balancing uni at UCL, two startups, marketing work at an AI company, cooking, travelling, UGC with 10+ brands, and building algo models for horse racing and forex. It sounds like a lot, but I am really just an average guy trying to learn and get a little better each day.

People ask how I manage it, and the truth is that I am still figuring it out. What helps is actually enjoying the work. When you like what you are building, it stops feeling like pressure and becomes something you naturally spend time on. I try to check in with myself often, understand what is helping me grow, and learn through action. If something works, I continue. If it does not, I adjust and move on.

I have also learned that you do not need to be special to make progress. Consistency and small habits matter more than talent. I try to stay organised, focus on what I can control, and avoid comparing myself to people who are on completely different paths. Most progress happens slowly and quietly. Curiosity helps a lot too. When I feel stuck, I look for better questions instead of forcing myself to grind harder.

The National Stock Exchange (NSE) has announced major changes in derivative contract lot sizes, which are important for all futures and options traders. As per the update, the existing lot sizes will continue for all weekly and monthly contracts until December 30, 2025. After that, revised lot sizes are expected to come into effect.

According to the proposed revision, the NIFTY lot size may reduce from 75 to 65, BANKNIFTY from 35 to 30, FINNIFTY from 65 to 60, and MIDCPNIFTY from 140 to 120. The primary aim of this move is to reduce the capital requirement for traders and improve overall risk management in the derivatives market.

A lower lot size means traders will need less margin, making F&O trading more accessible for retail and small-capital participants. This change is especially beneficial for beginners, as it helps in controlling risk exposure. At the same time, experienced traders will need to reassess their position sizing, strategies, and risk planning.

Overall, this step by NSE is seen as a positive move toward creating a more inclusive, balanced, and trader-friendly derivatives market. If you actively trade in futures and options, understanding and preparing for these changes in advance will be crucial for long-term success.

Overall, the data reflects a modern reality where borders are becoming less restrictive for talent, and individual aspirations increasingly shape national migration patterns.

The Space Shuttle and Buran represent two of the most iconic space programs born during the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union. While both orbiters looked strikingly similar, their philosophies and execution were very different. NASAâ€™s Space Shuttle was designed as a reusable spacecraft capable of carrying astronauts, satellites, and large payloads into low Earth orbit. It flew multiple missions over three decades and played a key role in building the International Space Station.

Buran, on the other hand, was the Soviet Unionâ€™s answer to the Shuttle. What made it unique was its fully automated design. Buran completed only one orbital flight in 1988, flying without a crew and landing autonomously, a technological achievement far ahead of its time. Despite its success, the program was discontinued due to the collapse of the Soviet Union and budget constraints.

This comparison highlights how geopolitics, economics, and technology shape space exploration. Both programs pushed the boundaries of engineering and left a lasting legacy that continues to influence modern spacecraft design. They remain powerful symbols of an era when space was not just about science, but also global dominance.

The distinct salutes of the Indian armed forces are steeped in history and symbolism, reflecting the unique ethos of each service branch. The Indian Army's salute involves an open palm facing forward, a gesture signifying respect, trust, and the absence of any hidden weaponsâ€”a tradition rooted in chivalry and transparency. In contrast, the Indian Navy's salute is executed with the palm facing downwards towards the ground. This practice originated in the age of sail, when sailors' hands were often stained with tar, oil, and grease from ship work; the downward-facing palm was a way to respectfully conceal soiled hands from superiors.
The Indian Air Force (IAF) developed its own unique salute later, holding the palm at a precise 45-degree angle to the ground. This specific angle is intended to symbolize the force's ambition and "progress toward the skies," aligning with their domain of operations. Prior to adopting this symbolic 45-degree angle, the IAF followed the Army's style. These variations highlight how military traditions adapt to reflect the operational environment and core values of each service, offering a fascinating glimpse into the pride and professionalism of India's soldiers, sailors, and airmen.
